ights how an\nasymmetric ambient field can result in preferred locations for reconnection,\nsubsequently guiding the direction of surges.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 Feb 2015 10:16:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-23"}
{"id":"1502.01843","submitter":"Julian Gonzalez-Ayala","authors":"Julian Gonzalez-Ayala and F. Angulo-Brown","title":"Is the $(3+1)-d$ nature of the universe a thermodynamic necessity?","comments":"3 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is well established that at early times, long before the time of\nradiation-matter equality, the universe could have been well described by a\nspatially flat, radiation only model. In this letter we consider the whole\nprimeval universe as a black body radiation (BBR) system in an $n-$dimensional\nEuclidean space. We propose that the $(3+1)-d$ nature of the universe could be\nthe result of a kind of thermodynamic selection principle stemming from the\nsecond law of thermodynamics. In regard the three spatial dimensions we suggest\nthat they were chosen by means of the minimization of the Helmholtz free energy\nper hypervolume unit, while the time dimension, as it is well known was the\nresult of the principle of increment of entropy for closed systems; that is,\nthe so-called arrow of time.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 Feb 2015 10:18:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 15 Feb 2015 18:47:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-02-17"}
